aa(lp86
VAnd if you buy all of this,
p87
aVand you think life is about computation, as I do,
p88
aVthen you look at big questions through the eyes of a computer scientist.
p89
aVSo one big question is, how does a baby know when to stop growing?
p90
aVAnd for molecular programming,
p91
aVthe question is how does your cell phone know when to stop growing?
p92
aV(Laughter)
p93
aVOr how does a computer program know when to stop running?
p94
aVOr more to the point, how do you know if a program will ever stop?
p95
aVThere are other questions like this, too.
p96
aVOne of them is Craig Venter's question.
p97
aVTurns out I think he's actually a computer scientist.
p98
aVHe asked, how big is the minimal genome
p99
aVthat will give me a functioning microorganism?
p100
aVHow few genes can I use?
p101
aVThis is exactly analogous to the question,
p102
aVwhat's the smallest program I can write
p103
aVthat will act exactly like Microsoft Word?
p104
aV(Laughter)
p105
aVAnd just as he's writing, you know, bacteria that will be smaller,
p106
aVhe's writing genomes that will work,
p107
aVwe could write smaller programs
p108
aVthat would do what Microsoft Word does.
p109
aa(lp110
VBut for molecular programming, our question is,
p111
aVhow many molecules do we need to put in that seed to get a cell phone?
p112
aVWhat's the smallest number we can get away with?
p113
aVNow, these are big questions in computer science.
p114
aVThese are all complexity questions,
p115
aVand computer science tells us that these are very hard questions.
p116
aVAlmost \u2014 many of them are impossible.
p117
aVBut for some tasks, we can start to answer them.
p118
aVSo, I'm going to start asking those questions
p119
aVfor the DNA structures I'm going to talk about next.
p120
aVSo, this is normal DNA, what you think of as normal DNA.
p121
aVIt's double-stranded, it's a double helix,
p122
aVhas the As, Ts, Cs and Gs that pair to hold the strands together.
p123
aVAnd I'm going to draw it like this sometimes,
p124
aVjust so I don't scare you.
p125
aVWe want to look at individual strands and not think about the double helix.
p126
aVWhen we synthesize it, it comes single-stranded,
p127
aVso we can take the blue strand in one tube
p128
aVand make an orange strand in the other tube,
p129
aVand they're floppy when they're single-stranded.
p130
aVYou mix them together and they make a rigid double helix.
p131
aVNow for the last 25 years,
p132
aVNed Seeman and a bunch of his descendants
p133
aVhave worked very hard and made beautiful three-dimensional structures
p134
aVusing this kind of reaction of DNA strands coming together.
p135
aVBut a lot of their approaches, though elegant, take a long time.
p136
aVThey can take a couple of years, or it can be difficult to design.
p137
aa(lp138
VSo I came up with a new method a couple of years ago
p139
aVI call DNA origami
p140
aVthat's so easy you could do it at home in your kitchen
p141
aVand design the stuff on a laptop.
p142
aVBut to do it, you need a long, single strand of DNA,
p143
aVwhich is technically very difficult to get.
p144
aVSo, you can go to a natural source.
p145
aVYou can look in this computer-fabricated artifact,
p146
aVand he's got a double-stranded genome \u2014 that's no good.
p147
aVYou look in his intestines. There are billions of bacteria.
p148
aVThey're no good either.
p149
aVDouble strand again, but inside them, they're infected with a virus
p150
aVthat has a nice, long, single-stranded genome
p151
aVthat we can fold like a piece of paper.
p152
aVAnd here's how we do it.
p153
aa(lp154
VThis is part of that genome.
p155
aVWe add a bunch of short, synthetic DNAs that I call staples.
p156
aVEach one has a left half that binds the long strand in one place,
p157
aVand a right half that binds it in a different place,
p158
aVand brings the long strand together like this.
p159
aVThe net action of many of these on that long strand
p160
aVis to fold it into something like a rectangle.
p161
aa(lp162
VNow, we can't actually take a movie of this process,
p163
aVbut Shawn Douglas at Harvard
p164
aVhas made a nice visualization for us
p165
aVthat begins with a long strand and has some short strands in it.
p166
aVAnd what happens is that we mix these strands together.
p167
aVWe heat them up, we add a little bit of salt,
p168
aVwe heat them up to almost boiling and cool them down,
p169
aVand as we cool them down,
p170
aVthe short strands bind the long strands
p171
aVand start to form structure.
p172
aVAnd you can see a little bit of double helix forming there.
p173
aVWhen you look at DNA origami,
p174
aVyou can see that what it really is,
p175
aVeven though you think it's complicated,
p176
aVis a bunch of double helices that are parallel to each other,
p177
aVand they're held together
p178
aVby places where short strands go along one helix
p179
aVand then jump to another one.
p180
aVSo there's a strand that goes like this, goes along one helix and binds \u2014
p181
aVit jumps to another helix and comes back.
p182
aVThat holds the long strand like this.
p183
aa(lp184
VNow, to show that we could make any shape or pattern
p185
aVthat we wanted, I tried to make this shape.
p186
aVI wanted to fold DNA into something that goes up over the eye,
p187
aVdown the nose, up the nose, around the forehead,
p188
aVback down and end in a little loop like this.
p189
aVAnd so, I thought, if this could work, anything could work.
p190
aVSo I had the computer program design the short staples to do this.
p191
aVI ordered them; they came by FedEx.
p192
aVI mixed them up, heated them, cooled them down,
p193
aVand I got 50 billion little smiley faces
p194
aVfloating around in a single drop of water.
p195
aVAnd each one of these is just
p196
aVone-thousandth the width of a human hair, OK?
p197
aa(lp198
VSo, they're all floating around in solution, and to look at them,
p199
aVyou have to get them on a surface where they stick.
p200
aVSo, you pour them out onto a surface
p201
aVand they start to stick to that surface,
p202
aVand we take a picture using an atomic-force microscope.
p203
aVIt's got a needle, like a record needle,
p204
aVthat goes back and forth over the surface,
p205
aVbumps up and down, and feels the height of the first surface.
p206
aVIt feels the DNA origami.
p207
aVThere's the atomic-force microscope working
p208
aVand you can see that the landing's a little rough.
p209
aVWhen you zoom in, they've got, you know,
p210
aVweak jaws that flip over their heads
p211
aVand some of their noses get punched out, but it's pretty good.
p212
aVYou can zoom in and even see the extra little loop,
p213
aVthis little nano-goatee.
